\maketitle
\begin<<206>>tex2html_deferred<<206>>\par\end<<207>>tex2html_deferred<<207>>
\section<<174>>Introduction<<174>>
\label<<175>>sec:introduction<<175>>
\begin<<208>>tex2html_deferred<<208>>\par\end<<209>>tex2html_deferred<<209>>
In May 2008 the research group around Prof. Barbara K\"onig at the Institute of Zoology of the University of Zurich decided to take their research in the field of Animal Behaviour to the next level. Especially interested in the complex social behaviour of house mice \textit<<176>>(Mus domesticus)<<176>> (see section \ref<<177>>subsec:socialbehaviour<<177>> on page \pageref<<178>>subsec:socialbehaviour<<178>> for details) they had the idea to design an automated system, to collect time and position data of mice living in a shed.
\begin<<210>>tex2html_deferred<<210>>\par\end<<211>>tex2html_deferred<<211>>
\subsection<<179>>Motivation<<179>>
\label<<180>>subsec:motivation<<180>>
The motivation for such an effort is to obtain a statistically relevant set of data to develop, test and prove scientific thesis about the social behaviour of the house mice. The research interests are outlined in section \ref<<181>>sec:biolhousemice<<181>> on page \pageref<<182>>sec:biolhousemice<<182>>. An automated system has the advantage that the data are collected without disturbing the mice in their natural behavior.
\begin<<212>>tex2html_deferred<<212>>\par\end<<213>>tex2html_deferred<<213>>
My personal motivation comes from the interest in informatics and my study in biology. The project gave me a lot of room to explore and enhance my skills in informatics while working on a biological topic. Additionally I am interested in the \textit<<183>>network approach<<183>> to analyze complex social behaviour by the use of \textit<<184>>Graph theory<<184>>\cite<<185>>wiki:graph_theory<<185>>. This approach is outlined in section \ref<<186>>sec:netexp<<186>> on page \pageref<<187>>sec:netexp<<187>>. 
\begin<<214>>tex2html_deferred<<214>>\par\end<<215>>tex2html_deferred<<215>>
\subsection<<188>>Task<<188>>
\label<<189>>subsec:task<<189>>
This approach of collecting data is challenging, as it includes several tasks which can be handled only using informatics on a level, that biologists usually can't cope with.
\begin<<216>>tex2html_deferred<<216>>\par\end<<217>>tex2html_deferred<<217>>
The system collecting the data in the shed has been developed and constructed by \textit<<190>>New Behaviour<<190>>. For further information about the design and operation of the system please see section \ref<<191>>subsec:collectspatialpos<<191>> on page \pageref<<192>>subsec:collectspatialpos<<192>>.     
\begin<<218>>tex2html_deferred<<218>>\par\end<<219>>tex2html_deferred<<219>>
Thus, the main task for my master thesis was to create an informatics framework which stores the data and make it accessible to the users, which are mainly the researchers involved in the house mice project.
\begin<<220>>tex2html_deferred<<220>>\par\end<<221>>tex2html_deferred<<221>>
\subsubsection<<193>>Storing and Accessing the Data<<193>>
\label<<194>>subsubsec:storeaccess<<194>>
The sheer amount of data expected to be collected by the automated system, has to be stored in a secure and stable way. This can be achieved by the use of a \ac<<195>>RDBMS<<195>> (RDBMS) (see section \ref<<196>>subsec:datastorage<<196>> on page \pageref<<197>>subsec:datastorage<<197>>).
\begin<<222>>tex2html_deferred<<222>>\par\end<<223>>tex2html_deferred<<223>>
To access the data, an easy to handle user interface must be available, which facilitates the data exploration and export (see section \ref<<198>>subsec:dataccess<<198>> on page \pageref<<199>>subsec:dataccess<<199>>). 
\begin<<224>>tex2html_deferred<<224>>\par\end<<225>>tex2html_deferred<<225>>
\subsubsection<<200>>Additional Tasks<<200>>
\label<<201>>subsubsec:additional<<201>>
Additionally the user should be provided with an interface to administrate attribute data of the mice (see section \ref<<202>>subsec:dataattr<<202>> on page \pageref<<203>>subsec:dataattr<<203>>) and to carry out some simple data analysis methods.
\begin<<226>>tex2html_deferred<<226>>\par\end<<227>>tex2html_deferred<<227>>
Last but not least, some functionality should be present to be able to analyze the data according to the network approach (see section \ref<<204>>sec:netexp<<204>> on page \pageref<<205>>sec:netexp<<205>>).
<tex2html_endfile>#/Users/rico/Documents/workspace/miceminer_thesis/src/introduction.tex#
